  4. [6 marks] Implement a 5-fold cross-validation (CV) procedure to calculate the average F1 score on each of the 5 folds using Logistic Regression. Write your own code for this question. That is, do not use any functions from other packages such as caret. However, you may use caret to create the folds and also compute the F1 score within each fold via confusionMatrix for this part. Use the set.seed(5003) line to ensure you get the same output on each run.

    set.seed(5003)

    Solution:

    set.seed(5003)
library(caret)
fold <- createFolds(q2.dat$classes, k = 5)
test.fold.sizes <- vapply(fold, length, numeric(1))
# For convenience, put the 5 fold CV sets into a list
split.data.into.folds <- function(x, dat, n = nrow(dat)) {
    which.group = factor(ifelse(seq(n) %in% x, "Test", "Training"))
    split(dat, which.group)
}
training.test <- lapply(fold, split.data.into.folds, dat = q2.dat, n = nrow(q2.dat))
fitted.log.models <- function(x, k = 5, label.name = "classes") {
    log.model <- glm(classes ~ ., data = x$Training, family = binomial(link = "logit"))
    predicted <- factor(unname(ifelse(predict(log.model, newdata = x$Test) > 0.5, 2, 1)))
    observed <- x$Test[[label.name]]
    list(predicted = predicted, observed = observed)
}
log.output <- lapply(training.test, fitted.log.models)
accuracy.within <- vapply(log.output, function(x) mean(x$observed == x$predicted), numeric(1))
accuracy.within
    ## Fold1 Fold2 Fold3 Fold4 Fold5 
##  0.77  0.74  0.78  0.76  0.72
    mean(accuracy.within)
    ## [1] 0.754
    f1.within <- vapply(log.output, function(x) {
  cM <- caret::confusionMatrix(x$predicted, x$observed, positive = "2")
  cM[["byClass"]][["F1"]]
}, numeric(1))

Question 3

The standard multiple regression model with two features assumes that the response and features follow the model \[ Y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 + \beta_2 X_2 + \varepsilon \qquad \varepsilon \sim \mathcal N(0, \sigma^2). \] This can lead to the likelihood model (you do not need to show this) where the log likelihood of the parameters \(\boldsymbol{\theta} = \left( \beta_0, \beta_1, \beta_2, \sigma\right)\) is given by \[ \mathcal L(\boldsymbol{\theta}|\mathcal X) = \begin{cases} -\infty, & \qquad \text{if } \sigma < 0;\\ -\frac{n}{2}\log(2 \pi) - n\log (\sigma) - \frac{1}{2\sigma^2} \sum_{i = 1}^n (Y_i - \beta_0 - \beta_1 X_{1i} - \beta_2X_{2i})^2, & \qquad \text{otherwise}.\end{cases} \] where \(\mathcal X = (Y_1, \ldots, Y_n, X_{11}, \ldots, X_{1n}, X_{21}, \ldots, X_{2n})\)

For this question consider estimating a linear model using both the standard least squares fitting procedure using lm and an approach using the method of Maximum Likelihood Estimation (MLE). In particular, consider the BostonHousing data available in the mlbench package with the median value of the housing as the response (medv) and the predictors being the number of rooms (rm) and the percentage of lower status of the population (lstat) respectively. It can be loaded using the code below

data(BostonHousing, package = "mlbench")
q3.dat <- subset(BostonHousing, select = c("medv", "lstat", "rm"))

  1. [2 marks] Inspect the q3.dat data, determining the dimension of the data and produce a matrix scatterplot (using the function pairs or other equivalent function).

    Solution:

    data(BostonHousing, package = "mlbench")

  2. [2 marks] Fit the linear regression using the lm function in R and extract the regression coefficients (the \(\beta\) values) and the estimate of \(\sigma\).

    Solution:

    simple.lm <- lm(medv ~ rm + lstat, data = q3.dat)
lm.coefs <- coef(simple.lm)
lm.sigma <- sigma(simple.lm)
lm.estimates <- c(lm.coefs, lm.sigma)
lm.estimates
    ## (Intercept)          rm       lstat             
##  -1.3582728   5.0947880  -0.6423583   5.5402574

  3. [3 marks] Define a function in R that computes the negative log-likelihood as a function of \(\boldsymbol{\theta}\) defined above. (Note \(\boldsymbol{\theta} = (\beta_0, \beta_1, \beta_2, \sigma)\) has 4 elements and will require a function with four input arguments e.g. fun <- function(w, x, y, z) has four arguments w, x, y, z) Solution:

    n <- nrow(q3.dat)
y <- q3.dat[["medv"]]
x1 <- q3.dat[["rm"]]
x2 <- q3.dat[["lstat"]]
negLogLikelihood <- function(beta0 = 0, beta1 = 0, beta2 = 0, sigma = 1) {
    if (sigma < 0)
      return(Inf)
    else 
       out <- n/2 * log(2 * pi) + n * log(sigma) + 1/(2 * sigma^2) * sum((y - beta0 - beta1 * x1 - beta2 * x2)^2)
    out
}

  4. [2 marks] As an alternative algorithm to estimate the regression coefficients and \(\sigma\), use the q3.dat data to compute the MLE of \(\boldsymbol{\theta}\) using the using the stats4::mle function (i.e. the function mle in the stats4 package) or via a grid search if you prefer. Solution:

    theta.mle <- stats4::mle(minuslogl = negLogLikelihood)
theta.mle <- theta.mle@coef
theta.mle
    ##     beta0     beta1     beta2     sigma 
## -1.258765  5.086072 -0.645697  5.517570

  5. [2 marks] Compare the outputs generated from lm and the MLE method above and comment. Solution:
